			<h1 class="sectionTitle">About TEDxUMaine</h1>
			<p class="bodyText">The first TEDx event on the University of Maine campus, sponsored by the Maine Journal publication, strives to share the experiences of exceptional University of Maine students through their own voices. The event will be comprised of six to eight student speakers as well as selected TED videos from past TED talks and live musical entertainment. The four hour event will include an hour long intermission in which audience members and speakers can eat lunch, network, and share ideas.</p>

			<h1 class="sectionTitle">Student Speakers</h1>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">Stephanie Whalley</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Stephanie graduated from Calvin College in Grand Rapids, Michigan with a B.S. in Biology focusing on plant biology and a B.A. in Political Science focusing on international relations. She is currently pursuing a Masters of Science in Ecology and Environmental Science within the School of Economics at the University of Maine. Her course work and research focus on energy economics. She is currently a research assistant within the School of Economics and works under the guidance of Dr. Sharon Klein. Her research interests include energy policy, sustainable energy, and the use of interdisciplinary study to address environmental issues facing society.</p>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">Jeshua Serdynski</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Jeshua Serdynski is a 4th year History major at the University of Maine in Orono, ME, and attends college with the goal in mind of obtaining his doctorate in global environmental history and becoming a university professor. He is currently finishing his undergraduate program while taking graduate level courses. He assists a professor with History 105 as a volunteer assistant, tutor Psychology and Sociology through the Tutor Program on campus.</p>
			<h3 class="studentTitle">Shelby Saucier</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Shelby is a first year graduate student in the School of Policy and International Affairs. Passionate about traveling, Shelby has been to India twice, Tanzania, Africa, all over the east coast of China, lived in Costa Rica for a while, and a few other places as well. Ultimately she wants to make a difference in the world, likely focused on women's education efforts in Southern India or Eastern Africa. After graduation she plans to move to Ethiopia to advocate for women's and children's rights to education and empowerment.</p>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">Jana Darlington</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Jana is a 20 year old woman, born and raised in the city of Boston. The child of an immigrant mother and a Marine father. She aiming to better public health and open minds.</p>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">Isaiah Mansour</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Growing up in Fairfield, Connecticut, Isaiah always had a passion for marine science, music, and creative writing. He is the bass player of the University of Maine Jazz Band, the University of Maine Symphonic Band, and the University of Maine Orchestra. Isaiah works on campus at the Aquaculture Research Center, and he is a proud new brother of the Alpha Tau Omega Fraternity. Most recently committed he committed himself to integrating creative writing and music by composing spoken word pieces over repeated sections of music called 'loops', played using my bass guitar and a complicated effects board.</p>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">John Bell, Richard Corey, Bethany Engstrom</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">John Bell is a software developer, writer, and researcher at the University of Maine. His work ranges from software preservation and digital art to web applications and augmented reality, and has been featured in diverse outlets like WIRED, Leonardo Electronic Almanac, and Harvard Law's Berkman Center for Internet & Society. He is co-author of the book <i>10 PRINT CHR$(205.5+RND(1));: GOTO 10</i> &#45; written in a single voice on a wiki along with nine other authors &#45; that looked at the cultural and technological foundations of early home computer use. Current projects include the Alliance for Networking Visual Culture's Scalar semantic web publishing platform and the Media Ecology Project at Dartmouth College. </p>

			<p class="bodyText">Richard Corey is the Director of Operations for the VEMI Lab, an installation artist, and a founding member of the Core 5 Incident. In the VEMI Lab he manages multiple projects dealing with virtual space and human interaction. His artwork involves a combination of psychological marketing and displacement of reality, all of which stems from his 16 years as owner of the marketing firm Artistek Design. Corey puts his design and marketing skills to use as a key member of the collaborative group the Core 5 Incident. He teaches at the University of Maine in Intermedia, Computer and Information Science, and Innovative Communication Design. Corey earned an MFA in Intermedia in 2011, and he is currently ABD with his PhD in Intermedial Collaborative Practices. </p>

			<p class="bodyText">Bethany Engstrom explores the perception of experience and space through objects, installation, audio, and video. Living and working in Belfast, Maine, Bethany received a BA in Art History from the University of Maine in 2002, her MFA in Intermedia from University of Maine in 2011 and currently is an Interdisciplinary PhD candidate at the University of Maine. She was a 2013 fellow at Mildred&#39;s Lane and her work has been included in a number of exhibitions in conjunction with UMaine, including Freeze Pop in 2008, Class Action in 2009 and Without Borders VI, VII and VIII and as well as in recent exhibitions at Asymmetrick Arts in Rockland, Maine and the Center for Maine Contemporary Art in Rockport, Maine. Along with her creative work, she is currently Research for Program Initiatives for the Intermedia MFA Program at the University of Maine and teaches courses in the program. Bethany also works at the Center for Maine Contemporary Art part-time and is a co-founder of the collaborative group the Core 5 Incident.</p>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">Graham Morehead</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Graham Morehead is currently a candidate for the Master of Science degree in Computer Science from The University of Maine. He began this program in 2010 with a focus in natural language processing. This focus moved subsequently to complex systems and ecological modeling. Morehead was born in Boston where he lived much of his life, eventually attending Boston University for Physics. He spent six years living overseas and has lived in Maine since early 2008. He has worked in various technology fields, including speech recognition, systems integration, app development, machine learning, statistical analysis, project management, linguistics, and IT management. Future goals include a sustained interest in complexity and its applications to language technologies.</p>

			<h3 class="studentTitle">Kyle Stetson</h3> 
			<p class="bodyText">Kyle is a fifth year political science major at the University of Maine. This Fall, he began a company called Fields of Blue Aquaponic Technologies with a few friends with the goal of creating and selling aquaponic gardening systems to home and business owners in Maine.</p>
			
